When you’re building reusable Angular components, it’s easy to focus on business logic and overlook how HTML itself behaves.
I recently ran into a bug that looked completely random:

• Some instances of a shared component displayed a native browser tooltip.

• Others behaved perfectly.

• Even stranger, the tooltip appeared when hovering over child elements that never defined a tooltip.
After digging through templates, inspecting rendered HTML, and comparing working versus broken components, the root cause turned out to be a naming collision between a component input and a global HTML attribute.
Here’s what happened, why it happens, and how you can avoid it in your own Angular applications.
The Bug
Imagine you have a reusable card component that accepts a heading.
@Component({
selector: 'app-info-card',
templateUrl: './info-card.html'
})
export class InfoCardComponent {
@Input() title!: string;
}Most developers use it like this:
<app-info-card
[title]="'Project Overview'">
</app-info-card>
